As with most perovskites, NaNbO$_{3}$ (Lueshite) exists in a variety of forms depending on temperature and composition. Many of these phases are identified in (Mitchell, 2014).  There is no consistent naming scheme that we are aware of, so we list the structures by space group.  All the structure are identified in (Mitchell, 2014) unless otherwise noted.  The paper does not give phase boundaries, so we will only indicate the temperatures at which the measurements were made. \begin{itemize} \item Synthetic Lueshite in orthorhombic \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_oP40_57_cd_e_cd2e-001}{space group $Pbcm$ \#57}. \item (Mitchell, 2014) find naturally occurring Lueshite in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_oP20_62_c_cd_a-001}{$Pnma$ CaTiO$_{3}$ phase}. \item (Vousden, 1951) found a ferroelectric Lueshite in \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_oP40_17_abcd_2e_abcd4e-001}{space group $P222_{1}$. (this structure) \#17}. \item At 575 and 600$^\circ$C Lueshite is in the base-centered orthorhombic \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_oC40_63_2c_d_efg-001}{space group $Cmcm$ \#63}. \item At 625$^\circ$C, Lueshite is in the orthorhombic \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_tP10_127_c_a_bg-001}{space group $P4/mbm$ \#127}. \item At 650 and 675$^\circ$C, and presumably at higher temperatures, NaNbO$_{3}$ is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_cP5_221_a_c_b-001}{cubic perovskite ($E2_{1}$) structure}. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-0.25in} 
 (Downs, 2003) identifies this as a ``possible polymorph of \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_oP40_57_cd_e_cd2e-001}{lueshite}.'' 
 If the aflow parameters are set to {\tt --params}$=a,1,\sqrt{8},1/2,0,0,1/2,1/2,0,0,1/2,0,0,3/8,1/2,1/2,3/8,1/4,1/4,3/8,3/4,1/4,3/8,1/4,3/4,3/8,3/4,3/4,3/8$ then this structure is equivalent to \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_cP5_221_a_c_b-001}{cubic perovskite $E2_{1}$}.
